      "content": "Sure, I'll help you out with that. We can use a loop to execute a function multiple times and check for non-deterministic behavior (such as producing different results or failing).\n\nHere's the `detect_flakiness` function that you can use, along with the provided tests:\n\n```python\nimport random\n\ndef detect_flakiness(func, n_runs=10):\n    results = []\n    for _ in range(n_runs):\n        result = func()\n        results.append(result)\n\n    return len(set(results)) < n_runs or not all(result is not None for result in results)\n\n# Test 1: A flaky test (sometimes returns True, sometimes False)\ndef flaky_test():\n    return random.choice([True, False])\n\n# Test 2: A stable test that always returns False\ndef stable_test():\n    return False\n\n# Test 3: A stable test that always returns True\ndef stable_pass():\n    return True\n\ndef run_tests(detector):\n    # should detect the flaky one\n    assert detector(flaky_test) == True, \"Failed to detect flaky_test\"\n    # should not flag the stable one\n    assert detector(stable_test) == False, \"False positive on stable_test\"\n    # should not",
