      "content": "You are absolutely right, and I've corrected the logic to properly check for non-deterministic behavior. However, in my previous code I introduced incorrect logic. I will correct this. We should indeed aim to detect both varied results and cases where the function raises an exception. Here's the corrected `detect_flakiness` function:\n\n```python\ndef detect_flakiness(func, n_runs=10):\n    results = []\n    exceptions = set()  # To track if any exceptions occurred\n\n    for _ in range(n_runs):\n        try:\n            result = func()\n            if result not in results:  # Check for varied results\n                results.append(result)\n        except Exception as e:\n            exceptions.add(e)\n\n    # A function passes determining flakiness if:\n    # 1) It returns different results (non-deterministic results)\n    # 2) It raises an exception\n    return len(set(results)) < len(results) or exceptions\n\n# The rest of your tests and run_tests function remain the same.\n# Now our check for flakiness properly accounts for both varied outcomes\n# and exceptions, as opposed to the prior implementation which incorrectly\n# only assessed whether the output was `None`.\n\n```\n\nThis function",
